[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.680]   This is a Kehl blog post from August 34, 2005 titled, "Lessons from WinFS."
[00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:09.920]   Microsoft put WinFS into beta today, so it seems like a good time to talk about WinFS and what it
[00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:14.720]   tells us about the future of file systems and databases. WinFS is a new file system that was
[00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:18.800]   originally supposed to be in the Windows Vista release, Nae Longhorn, which is now slated for
[00:00:18.800 --> 00:00:23.920]   delivery in Fall 2006. Vista has been delayed several times. The word on the street was that
[00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:27.920]   those delays were largely due to problems developing WinFS, leading to the conclusion
[00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:32.640]   that WinFS was deliberately de-scubbed from Vista in order to help Microsoft finally ship from Vista
[00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:38.000]   in order to help Microsoft finally ship it. Microsoft calls WinFS a unified storage system.
[00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:42.800]   As far as I can tell, it's a new XML-based file system. When you consider that Microsoft is,
[00:00:42.800 --> 00:00:47.600]   one, moving the Office document formats to XML, two, embracing metadata tags with features like
[00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:52.160]   smart tags in Office, and three, developing a new XML-based file system, you can get your
[00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:58.400]   first lesson from WinFS. Lesson 1, XML is important. It is a trend, not a fad. One duty of a file
[00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:03.200]   system is helping you organize and subsequently find things. That's primarily been accomplished
[00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:07.760]   through a hierarchical directory structure. Most people don't do a good job organizing things,
[00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:11.920]   whether it's paper files or their computer equivalent. Some problems are human nature,
[00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:16.160]   we just aren't strict or repeatable in building ad hoc taxonomies. Others are caused by the
[00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:21.760]   hierarchical requirement that a file end up in one place. For example, does the 2005 operating plan
[00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:26.800]   presentation belong in the 1104 board meeting folder or the 2005 plan folder? While you could
[00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:31.840]   use short CITA. Oots2, effectively, to put the file in both places, they are error-prone and
[00:01:31.840 --> 00:01:36.160]   few people actually use them. So, while directories are most certainly helpful, we know that they
[00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:40.320]   should be complemented with search if you actually want to find anything. It must be embarrassing to
[00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:45.360]   Microsoft that customers have resorted to third-party search engines, such as Google Desktop or X1,
[00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:51.040]   to search for information in their file system. This leads to lesson 2. Lesson 2, search is
[00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:55.280]   important. Hierarchies alone don't let you find things. When you think about searching a file
[00:01:55.280 --> 00:02:00.720]   system, two types of searches come to mind. The first is text search, e.g., find me all files
[00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:05.920]   containing the word "semantic." The second is metadata search, e.g., find me all files created
[00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:10.960]   by stroline or about RDF. Historically, experts believe that you needed librarians with controlled
[00:02:10.960 --> 00:02:15.920]   vocabularies and rigorously defined taxonomies in order to get value from metadata tagging.
[00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:20.240]   Increasingly, people believe that while the old approach does indeed work, that you can accomplish
[00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:24.400]   a lot with an organic approach where authors tag their content in an ad hoc fashion,
[00:02:24.400 --> 00:02:29.040]   sometimes called a folksonomy. This is a radically different philosophy that nonetheless produces a
[00:02:29.040 --> 00:02:34.000]   valuable result. For an example of the power of ad hoc tagging, check out Flickr. This leads to
[00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.920]   our third lesson. Lesson 3, metadata is important. Metadata has always been the stepchild of data,
[00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:44.800]   and I'd always quipped that "Metadata companies tend to produce meta-revenues." In the future,
[00:02:44.800 --> 00:02:49.680]   this will be decreasingly true. In fact, I'd argue there is a Maslow's hierarchy analogy between data
[00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:54.640]   metadata and between physiological safety needs. You only worry about safety after you have food
[00:02:54.640 --> 00:02:59.680]   and water. You only worry about metadata after you have data. To steal an example from my past life
[00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:04.000]   at Business Objects, only after you know sales of watches in NYC in April do you wonder when
[00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.400]   the data was refreshed, from which system did it come, and was it net of an allowance for returns?
[00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:13.040]   One disconcerting thing I've heard about WinFS is that Bill Gates himself dictated that it be
[00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:18.240]   implemented on top of SQL Server. On one hand, you can understand that as Chief Software Architect,
[00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:22.800]   that Gates doesn't want Microsoft running around with redundant DBMSs and file systems.
[00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:29.120]   For example, Outlook uses neither the file system nor one of Microsoft's DBMSs (i.e. Access) SQL
[00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:34.000]   Server to store messages in your personal folders. Outlook seems to have implemented a file system
[00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:39.440]   within a mail client that loads everything into one giant .ost file on your machine. Mine is nearly
[00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:44.320]   1 GB. On the other hand, the Achilles heel of the relational database has always been modeling
[00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:49.600]   hierarchy. File systems or hierarchical.xml is strictly hierarchical. So while I'm sure it
[00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:53.440]   sounded really good in a meeting to say something like, "Let's put all our wood behind our one
[00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:58.560]   strategic DBMS arrow in SQL Server," I am also quite sure that such a decision could easily
[00:03:58.560 --> 00:04:02.240]   doom the project to failure. Lesson 4. Beware things that model
[00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:07.600]   hierarchy in a relational database. Time will tell how well Microsoft has implemented WinFS.
[00:04:07.600 --> 00:04:13.120]   Time will also tell how the line between DBMS and file system plays out. For the past 20 years,
[00:04:13.120 --> 00:04:18.080]   DBMS vendors have said, "The file system is dead. Long live the database." And for the past 20
[00:04:18.080 --> 00:04:22.960]   years, about 80% of all information has resisted databases, stubbornly remaining on the file
[00:04:22.960 --> 00:04:28.240]   system, increasingly accessed via search engines. I believe the explanation for all this is simple.
