[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.280]   This is a KEL blog post from September 9, 2005 titled, "We Seek the Grail."
[00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:09.280]   Everyone knows that content is largely unmanaged, untapped as an enterprise resource.
[00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:14.720]   We've all heard the soundbite usually attributed to IDC that 80% of enterprise information is
[00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:19.360]   unstructured and not kept in a database. We all believe there is a lot of value in tapping into
[00:00:19.360 --> 00:00:24.400]   that content. So we're all on the same mission, right? We're all seeking the same grail. Or are
[00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:29.280]   we? As a long-time data guy, I know well the grail that data people seek. It's the data content
[00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:33.360]   integration grail. The stump speech I used at Business Objects went something like this.
[00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:38.080]   Oh yeah, there's that other stuff. Content, I think it's called. That doesn't fit in your relational
[00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:42.320]   databases, so you can't access it with our BI tools. Well, I guess it's obvious what you want
[00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:46.160]   to do with that content. Structure it up and summarize it so you can shove it in the warehouse
[00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:50.560]   right alongside your data and then make reports on it using our tools. When you have a 1B data
[00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:55.120]   business, you see content through data-colored glasses. The example I used in my past life was
[00:00:55.120 --> 00:00:59.760]   customer service emails. What you really want is to take the hundreds of feedback emails that flow
[00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:04.160]   in every week and make a crosstab report that groups them along two dimensions, by product
[00:01:04.160 --> 00:01:09.120]   and by tone, i.e. positive, negative, neutral. In that way, you can take a mass of otherwise
[00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:13.280]   useless, unstructured content and use it to enrich your existing dashboards and reports.
[00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:18.640]   It's a good example. It's a real example. Lots of people want to do it. But it is not the only
[00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:23.760]   example. Integration with data is not the sole reason to unlock content. Many important content
[00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:28.640]   applications have little or no data content integration angle. Next, custom publishing.
[00:01:28.640 --> 00:01:34.240]   Next, content delivery. Next, contract management. Next, content integration. Next, knowledge
[00:01:34.240 --> 00:01:40.000]   management. Next, RFP management. Next, technical publications. Next, financial publishing. Next,
[00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:45.280]   search and discovery. Next, search and discovery. Next, content intelligence, just to name a few.
[00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:49.360]   If you have a 2TB data warehouse and you want to summarize some unstructured content into data
[00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:53.360]   and then load it alongside your existing tables, then you should require a text analytics tool to
[00:01:53.360 --> 00:01:57.600]   do the summarization and then store the resulting data in your data warehouse. If, on the other
[00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:01.360]   hand, you are working on systems that need to query, manipulate, and render content, such as
[00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:06.080]   those listed above, then I'd argue you are seeking a different grail. It's about content for content
[00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:11.120]   sake and not about turning content into data. So the question is, not do you seek the grail,
[00:02:11.120 --> 00:02:16.000]   but indeed, which grail do you seek? This audio version was created by Grant Duncan and AI,
[00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:17.120]   with permission from Dave.
