[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.840]   This is a Kell blog post from September 20, 2005, titled "The Bifurcation of Search."
[00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:09.000]   I often hear the question asked, "What's after search?
[00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:10.720]   Find," one would hope.
[00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:13.960]   After all, searching's not the point; finding is.
[00:00:13.960 --> 00:00:17.120]   So the real question is, how can we improve find?
[00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:21.800]   And answering it requires separating the cases of internet and non-internet search applications.
[00:00:21.800 --> 00:00:25.560]   Let's do a brief history of internet search to see why.
[00:00:25.560 --> 00:00:29.800]   First-generation internet search engines analyze the content of a page to decide its relevance
[00:00:29.800 --> 00:00:31.640]   to a particular search.
[00:00:31.640 --> 00:00:35.980]   In effect, relevancy was determined by the page's author in deciding what words to use
[00:00:35.980 --> 00:00:39.080]   in his writing and what metatags to add to the page.
[00:00:39.080 --> 00:00:42.460]   This wasn't a bad way to start, but it lent itself to abuses.
[00:00:42.460 --> 00:00:46.000]   It wasn't long before spammers figured out how to head fake search engines into thinking
[00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.900]   their web pages were more relevant than the other guys.
[00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:53.800]   They put metatags on our pages that would repeat a keyword over and over, I-A-G, sex,
[00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:56.480]   in order to increase their relevancy to given searches.
[00:00:56.480 --> 00:00:59.880]   Thus was born search engine optimization.
[00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:03.440]   Google came along and suggested that the link structure of the web was a better way to determine
[00:01:03.440 --> 00:01:05.320]   relevancy than page content.
[00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:09.520]   I first read about this in the mid-1990s in an Esther Dyson newsletter and I remember
[00:01:09.520 --> 00:01:12.600]   that it struck me as a truly revolutionary idea.
[00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:16.660]   In effect, it said that relevancy should be determined by other webmasters.
[00:01:16.660 --> 00:01:20.520]   It hobbled the spammers, produced better internet search results, and combined with the idea
[00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:25.640]   of paid-for results borrowed from go2.com and propelled Google to great fame and fortune.
[00:01:25.640 --> 00:01:28.080]   But this idea is nearly 10 years old today.
[00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:31.900]   Search engine optimizers are learning how to beat it, and it has proven to be more effective
[00:01:31.900 --> 00:01:36.880]   for responding to common searches than those in the proverbial "long tail" of search.
[00:01:36.880 --> 00:01:40.920]   Most of the energy in the search community is dedicated to finding the next page rank,
[00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:44.420]   the next magic algorithm that will produce better search results and propel someone else
[00:01:44.420 --> 00:01:46.480]   to fame and fortune.
[00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:48.560]   Pundits seem split on what it will be.
[00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:53.340]   Various arguments include "next," "taxonomies," and "folksnomies" that help people navigate
[00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:55.840]   to the answer instead of searching for it.
[00:01:55.840 --> 00:02:00.760]   Next, dynamic clustering a la vivissimo, where search grouped into clusters that can be used
[00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:03.000]   to incrementally refine a search.
[00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.840]   Next, behavioral techniques that use cookies to watch some would say "spy on users"
[00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:11.960]   and their surfing habits, applying what is learned to bias or "personalize" search
[00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:12.960]   results.
[00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:16.620]   As a quick aside, I find somewhat amazing that Google appears to be doing reasonably well
[00:02:16.620 --> 00:02:19.960]   with their enterprise search appliance when the Google "secret sauce" is all about
[00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:21.600]   page rank and pagera.
[00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:23.840]   7k is all about link structure.
[00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:24.840]   Why?
[00:02:24.840 --> 00:02:28.360]   Because inside an enterprise, you typically don't have link structure to work with.
[00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:32.840]   Instead you have file folders full of marketing brochures, HR policies, sales presentations,
[00:02:32.840 --> 00:02:36.760]   contract templates, RFPs, etc., and nothing is linked together.
[00:02:36.760 --> 00:02:40.760]   That this is lost on most people is a triumph of branding and makes pagerink-free Google
[00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:44.000]   somewhat akin to caffeine-free jolt as a product.
[00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.360]   Searching the internet is fundamentally different from searching the corpus of content held
[00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:50.620]   by an enterprise, a publisher, or a government agency.
[00:02:50.620 --> 00:02:53.920]   The former is internet search and the latter is enterprise search.
[00:02:53.920 --> 00:02:57.240]   While I'll defer the question of how to make internet search better to those gurus who study
[00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:01.680]   it for a living, I'll propose a simple answer on how to make enterprise search better, make
[00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:06.680]   it more like a database, make it more like a database, make it more like a query.
[00:03:06.680 --> 00:03:08.860]   Database people don't search databases.
[00:03:08.860 --> 00:03:09.940]   They query them.
[00:03:09.940 --> 00:03:13.720]   They don't expect 10 links in a magical order that might answer their question.
[00:03:13.720 --> 00:03:15.960]   They expect a precise answer to their query.
[00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:20.560]   They don't expect to know there are 10, 2, 2, 35, 035 results and only be able to see
[00:03:20.560 --> 00:03:22.460]   the first 1,000 of them.
[00:03:22.460 --> 00:03:25.740]   They don't expect latency when a new document is added to the system.
[00:03:25.740 --> 00:03:29.180]   If a row is committed to the database, it is included in all answers from the moment
[00:03:29.180 --> 00:03:30.280]   after the commit.
[00:03:30.280 --> 00:03:34.320]   You don't wait two days or even 10 minutes to start including it in query results.
[00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:36.720]   I believe the future of enterprise search is here.
[00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:38.680]   It's all about two technologies.
[00:03:38.680 --> 00:03:41.240]   Next, XML markup enrichers.
[00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:45.960]   The broad category of products that input XML and output better XML, typically inserting
[00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:50.280]   markup to indicate things like entities, concepts, linguistics, and sentiment.
[00:03:50.280 --> 00:03:54.380]   Next, XQuery-based XML content servers, like MarkLogic.
[00:03:54.380 --> 00:03:58.600]   With these two technologies you can take a collection of documents, convert them to XML,
[00:03:58.600 --> 00:04:02.000]   enrich the XML markup, and then run powerful queries against them.
[00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.600]   The best search isn't search, it's query.
