[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.480]   This is a KEL blog post from September 29, 2005 titled "Uh Oh, It's Magic." As a self-described
[00:00:06.480 --> 00:00:10.560]   data turncoat, I confess that one of my goals in hopping the data content border when I joined
[00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:15.200]   Mark Logic was to bring lessons from the data world to the content world. I felt that far too
[00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:19.280]   few people had lived in both worlds and there would be a big opportunity to leverage my experience
[00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:23.680]   from one and the other. In today's posting, I'll share my thoughts on logic that I've learned from
[00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:27.760]   my years on the data side of the data content border. I'll start with an observation from the
[00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:31.680]   innovations in Search Conference this week in New York. In practically each session,
[00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:36.800]   speakers asked, "What is beyond search?" I was first shocked and then puzzled. I realized that
[00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:42.160]   in 20-plus years, I have never seen a category so preoccupied with its own demise. Database people
[00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:46.960]   don't spend their time asking, "What's beyond databases?" BI people don't obsess over what's
[00:00:46.960 --> 00:00:52.560]   beyond BI. Instead, they worry about improving and evolving their products. I think this preoccupation
[00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:56.720]   reveals that something is fundamentally wrong with search. Customers aren't happy with it.
[00:00:56.720 --> 00:01:00.400]   The sense you get is that while everyone is dissatisfied, no one's found anything better
[00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:05.120]   so we will all just muddle through with the least bad solution. Or, as one speaker bluntly put it,
[00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:09.760]   search sucks. I'll tell you one thing that I think is wrong with search — magic. If there's one
[00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:13.920]   lesson I learned in 20-plus years in the data world, it's that magic doesn't sell. Customers
[00:01:13.920 --> 00:01:18.800]   don't like magic. Consider the fate of data mining, for example. Data mining is infinitely
[00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:23.600]   more powerful than traditional business intelligence. Yet the BI market today is billions of dollars and
[00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:27.520]   growing while the data mining market remains stubbornly stuck in the tens of millions.
[00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:32.000]   How can that be? Why is it that the market for manual database query, enterprise reporting,
[00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.480]   and manual slice iced row analysis is 100 times bigger than the market for neural networking,
[00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:39.920]   case-based reasoning, genetic algorithms, decision trees, and the like?
[00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:43.200]   I have some direct experience here, which I'll share.
[00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:47.120]   I launched a data mining product at Business Objects. On the heels of our successful Business
[00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:52.160]   Objects 4.0, OLAP for the masses launch, we decided to put more analytic power on the desktop.
[00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:56.240]   We did a thorough evaluation of data mining products, signed an OEM contract with our chosen
[00:01:56.240 --> 00:02:00.240]   vendor, relabeled the product, and launched it as Business Miner, under the marketing banner
[00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:04.800]   Data Mining for the masses. As it turned out, the masses wanted nothing to do with data mining.
[00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:09.120]   The product died a quiet death a few years after its launch. We understood the technical
[00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:13.440]   issues with data mining — e.g., training sets, overtraining, extrapolation — when we launched
[00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:17.840]   the product. But those problems didn't kill Business Miner. Magic did. I chuckle when I see
[00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:22.080]   search vendors' chests thumping about Bayesian this or that in their marketing. I majored in math
[00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:26.000]   at Berkeley and barely understand Bayesian inferencing. Will your average customer do any
[00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.520]   better? When vendors think they're impressing customers with their algorithms, they're just
[00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:33.600]   scaring them. You only feel worse in knowing that each internet search engine claims to have the best
[00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:38.160]   relevance magic. But another speaker pointed out that the typical overlap among the top three is
[00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:43.360]   less than 5%. I'm not naive. I know that with content, the volume of information and the
[00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:48.400]   complexity of the task inevitably requires some magic. But the goal should be to, next,
[00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:53.360]   use as little magic as possible. Next, provide as much transparency as possible.
[00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:58.160]   Here is where XML comes to the rescue. What I like so much about MarkLogic-based solutions
[00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:02.080]   is that they have right mix of magic and pragmatism. Here's how they work.
[00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:07.680]   Next, you start with a collection of content. Next, if not in XML, we can convert it to XML.
[00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:13.440]   This involves low magic such as identifying basic structure, e.g., titles, sections, paragraphs.
[00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:18.400]   Next, then you can enrich that content. This can be done with high magic such as entity,
[00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:24.000]   fact, concept, and sentiment extractors, or with linguistic processors. Or this can be done with
[00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.000]   low magic, using heuristics and xQuery. Regardless of approach, I call this verifiable magic. It's
[00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:35.280]   not totally black box. The output of the magic is additional XML tags inserted in the original
[00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:40.240]   content, so you can read 100 documents and decide if they were correctly classified as positive,
[00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:45.600]   negative, or neutral. Or if people in place identification was correct. Or if, in context,
[00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:52.640]   Bob really is a noun and chip A, verb. Next, then you run xQuery against the enriched content.
[00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:57.600]   xQuery is a database query language, so there is no magic involved. You can leverage tags created
[00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:03.040]   either manually or through magic and run database-style queries against them. And yes, if you want
[00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:08.240]   relevance-ordered results, then there is some low magic TFIDF involved in that process. The
[00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:13.440]   thing I like about this model is the near-total separation of magic and non-magic. Use no magic
[00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:20.000]   or low magic to get XML. Use high magic if desired to insert more tags into it. Then use xQuery,
[00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.960]   basically no magic to run database-style queries against. The content. I think it's the right
[00:04:24.960 --> 00:04:29.840]   approach to the problem. This audio version was created by Grant Duncan and AI, with permission
[00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:31.840]   from Dave.
